	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Cameroon looking to expand sugar production </h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 October 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, a Cameroonian–Indian joint venture, Justin Sugar Mills, is set to invest in a 60,000-tonne expansion of national sugar production in Cameroon, at a projected cost of €91.4 million. This would increase current national sugar production by 50% and would take Cameroonian sugar production to within 10% of national consumption needs (180,000 tonnes production, compared to 200,000 tonnes consumption per annum).</p><p>The company is to grow and process sugar cane on 155,000 acres of land in Cameroon's East Region. Additionally, the investment will include a 16-megawatt electricity generation unit ‘which would burn waste from sugar processing to power the factory and nearby villages’. More than 5,000 direct and 2,500 indirect jobs are to be created in the region through this investment. According to press reports, the company has been supported by state aid, mainly in decreasing the import costs of industrial equipment.</p><p>This investment follows earlier government calls to increase national sugar production by investing in large-scale plantations and processing facilities in order to decrease dependency on imports. In March 2012, Sosucam, the state-managed sugar company, also announced a 7-year investment programme to increase sugar production worth €168 million. Sosucam is the main sugar producer, with annual production of 120,000 tonnes. Three other private companies, Nosuca, Sumoca and New Food, together supply less than 30,000 tonnes a year.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
