				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>With the state-owned company producing the major part of the country’s sugar output but not being able to satisfy consumption needs, Cameroon regularly faces a shortfall in sugar supplies with consequent domestic price pressures. Currently this is addressed through the granting of discretionary sugar import licences to private companies.</p><p>At the same time, according to press reports, Cameroonian sugar is being exported illegally, due to growing demand in neighbouring countries, which then pushes up domestic sugar prices.</p><p>In 2010, according to the UN COMTRADE database, Cameroon imported 74,000 tonnes of sugar, up since 2006 from as little as 33,000 tonnes per annum in some years.</p><p>Potentially these new investments could make a significant difference to local supplies, impacting on both availability and prices of sugar on local markets. However, in order to meet government objectives, investment levels will need to be sustained and issues related to informal cross-border trade will need to be addressed.&nbsp;</p>
		</div>
		
